00:15:33.090 --> 00:15:38.560
format to see how this works. Okay. Now
I'm going to show you another experiment

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:49.810
that actually I think gives you maybe a
slightly more subtle insight into how all

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:56.420
of this works. So what we do in this
experiment is we compare responses to

00:15:56.600 --> 00:16:03.220
pictures with responses to video clips.
By the way, just a small autobiographical

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:07.360
point here, we used to use pictures all
the time when we first went into the

00:16:07.540 --> 00:16:13.290
Bedouin village. We would just show people
pictures and the older Bedouin signers

00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:17.530
really had no idea what to do. And we
thought that, "Well, it's just a picture.

00:16:17.710 --> 00:16:21.400
Doesn't everybody know how to name a
picture? I mean, after all, you do that at

00:16:21.580 --> 00:16:26.600
first grade." And then it suddenly
emerged. "Duh, first grade. These people

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:31.130
never got to first grade."
It turns out that picture naming is a

00:16:31.310 --> 00:16:36.040
learned kind of task. There's nothing
natural about naming pictures. People

00:16:36.220 --> 00:16:41.750
living out there in the wild don't have
pictures that they could point at. So this

00:16:41.930 --> 00:16:50.350
was really a lesson, a cross-cultural
lesson, to us. We were interested in

00:16:50.530 --> 00:16:56.050
whether simply showing people a static
picture versus showing people a video

00:16:56.230 --> 00:17:00.880
would have an effect. And of course it
did, otherwise we wouldn't bother to show

00:17:01.060 --> 00:17:08.200
it to you, right? Okay. So this is what we
showed people. So here is simply a brush

00:17:08.380 --> 00:17:16.837
and here is a video clip of somebody using
the brush.

00:17:18.620 --> 00:17:24.290
Everybody sees that? Okay. And we compare
people's responses to those and it is of

00:17:24.470 --> 00:17:30.540
course actually what you might expect. So
when you show people a video, even

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:40.300
gesturers, they're much more likely to use
handling. But when you show gesturers a

00:17:40.480 --> 00:17:49.150
picture then they are much more likely to
use instruments. Now a little bit of

00:17:49.330 --> 00:17:58.820
tortured reasoning here, but the fact that
they were responding so overwhelmingly to

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.410
the handling response, the gesturers were
responding so overwhelmingly to the

00:18:03.590 --> 00:18:10.420
handling response even with the pictures,
shows you that there is this major

00:18:10.600 --> 00:18:18.620
difference between how the gesturers are
organizing their signal and how the

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:22.040
signers are organizing their symbol,
right.

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:29.960
So what we see is that there is this
difference, right? That it's been somehow

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:37.820
conventionalized and amplified in this one
sign language which is the Bedouin sign

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:45.430
language and even more so in the sign
language, in American sign language. I'm

00:18:45.610 --> 00:18:49.440
not going to talk about it here, but it
turns out that when you look at other sign

00:18:49.620 --> 00:18:53.690
languages, we looked at Israeli sign
language, it doesn't work that way. So I

00:18:53.870 --> 00:18:58.720
think what's going on is that signers pick
up, they pick up on these patterns, this

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:04.400
is what we've seen before in earlier
presentations. They're picking up on these

00:19:04.580 --> 00:19:10.670
patterns and what matters more is the
consistency of the abstract underlying

00:19:10.850 --> 00:19:17.064
pattern.
This is a very abstract notion of handling

00:19:17.064 --> 00:19:22.375
versus also depicting the instrument that
they are picking up on. And, by the way,

00:19:22.375 --> 00:19:28.430
when you show people pieces of fruit, this
doesn't happen because of course pieces of

00:19:28.430 --> 00:19:40.332
fruit are not instruments, at least
not usually. Okay. All right. I think the

00:19:40.332 --> 00:19:46.918
one takeaway lesson that is really
important is that people have a drive to

00:19:46.918 --> 00:19:52.509
communicate. We've talked about this. They
have a drive to share which Tecumseh Fitch

00:19:52.509 --> 00:19:59.204
coined this wonderful German word which is
mitteilungsbedürfnis which. . . only in

00:19:59.204 --> 00:20:03.449
German, right? But it basically means a
need to share. And what we're seeing in

00:20:03.449 --> 00:20:09.804
all of these cases is that you can
increase the power of your sharing by

00:20:09.804 --> 00:20:15.650
organizing your system and that's what is
going on here. So, thank you, and Carol

00:20:15.830 --> 00:20:18.443
thanks you as well.

